{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636018"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.9,0,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10248"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71584"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10248"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57080"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7157"},{"type":"tags","id":"10357"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24149"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71584"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum can be divided into three functional regions based on their primary inputs and outputs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the vestibulocerebellum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plans complex motor sequences","Maintains balance and equilibrium","Coordinates skilled voluntary movements","Controls speech and language","Regulates muscle tone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintenance of balance and equilibrium\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the vestibulocerebellum (flocculonodular lobe). It receives direct input from the vestibular nuclei and vestibular nerve, helping to coordinate head position and eye movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlanning complex motor sequences\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of the motor cortex and premotor areas in the frontal lobe, which are responsible for motor planning and sequencing of voluntary movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordination of skilled voluntary movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is specifically the function of the cerebrocerebellum (lateral hemispheres), which receives input from the cerebral cortex via pontine nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControl of speech and language\u003C/strong\u003E - Language function is controlled by Broca\u0027s and Wernicke\u0027s areas in the cerebral cortex. While the cerebellum helps coordinate speech movements, it does not process language\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulation of muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of the spinocerebellum (vermis and intermediate zones), which receives input from the spinal cord about proprioception\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibulocerebellum is phylogenetically the oldest part of the cerebellum and is sometimes called the archicerebellum. It processes vestibular information to help maintain balance during both static positions and movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The vestibulocerebellum consists of the flocculonodular lobe and receives primary input from the vestibular system.","The vestibulocerebellum helps maintain balance and equilibrium by coordinating head and eye movements.","The vestibulocerebellum is phylogenetically the oldest part of the cerebellum, also known as the archicerebellum."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57080"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57080"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T18:30:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-19T18:33:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10248"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71584"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud